mass vaccination arouses anxiety in some people but sentiments of civic duty and shared solidarity in others. This collection of essays gives a comparative overview of vaccination at different times, in widely different places and under different types of political regime. Core themes in the chapters include immunisation as an element of state formation; citizens' articulation of seeing (or not seeing) their needs incorporated into public health practice; allegations that donors of development aid have too much influence on third-world health policies; and an ideological shift that regards vaccines more as profitable commodities than as essential tools of public health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedicine (General). 0aVaccinationxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aVaccination.  aimmunisation.  amass immunisation campaigns.  anation-states.  aneo-liberalism.  astate formation.  avaccine production.1 aBenchimol, Jaime, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlume, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlume, Stuart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrimnes, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrillo, Ana María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Eun Kyung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenough, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenough, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolmberg, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmberg, Christine